data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The provider's underlying SDK (Cosmos DB SDK v3) is async-only, so EF Core previously shimmed sync calls by blocking on async ones — a pattern that risks deadlocks and thread pool starvation.

**In .NET 10**, you could keep sync calls working with the opt-in:
```csharp
options.UseCosmos(..., cosmosOptions =>
    cosmosOptions.AllowSynchronousIO());
```

**In .NET 11**, that API is gone. Every sync call — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — throws `InvalidOperationException` with no workaround.

### The fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods → `async` + `Async` suffix
- LINQ terminals → `ToListAsync()`, `FirstAsync()`, `CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`

This will ripple up through your call chain — all callers must also become `async`/`await` up to the controller level (which ASP.NET Core already supports natively).
